I"Ú<p>If <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brains-are-like-orchestras">brain activity</a> turns out to resemble a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/manifolds-formalize-emergence">manifold</a> <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neuroplasticity-is-like-protein-folding">changing its structure in time</a>, then forgetting and childhood amnesia can be explained by the fact that memories would be coded in locations on a manifold which are currently less accessible. The <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brain-is-like-hardware-mind-is-like-software">neural substrate</a> itself its changing, limiting access to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/mental-representations-connect-internal-with-external-state">parts of the mental space</a>. However, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/how-can-routine-cell-replacement-permit-psychological-continuity">psychological continuity seems to survive routine cell replacement</a> unscathed.</p>
